<HEADLINE>
Time travel/parallel worlds in roguelikes?
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Anders.Hell...@gmail.com </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-09-13T19:43:00 </POSTDATE>
My brain started working today and spat out a silly idea. It blathered
about a roguelike where you would travel between different worlds/
times. Your actions in one world, or in the past, would affect things
in the future/other world.

Musing I: Has it been done? I haven't heard of any RL:s on this theme,
but:
* The Legend of Zelda: A Link to the Past had a Light and a Dark
world, with travel to the light world being possible once you got a
certain object, and with portals to the dark world scattered across
the light one. Also, a grand total of one puzzle based on pulling a
lever in the light world to activate its counterpart machinery in the
dark world. (Entering the water castle.)
* Day of the Tentacle. You control three characters scattered in the
past, the present and the future. Some puzzles let you affect the
&quot;future&quot;, for example tricking the Founding Fathers into mandating the
existence of a vacuum cleaner in every home. (Which spawns a vacuum in
the &quot;future&quot; setting.)

I'm sure there's others. Maybe even an RL?

Musing II: What the heck would you be DOING in an RL heavily based on
the concept of time travel/parallell worlds? The most important
question before making one, if you ask me.
* Time police? Master Kaen has created a time machine and is now
beating up random people somewhere in the 18:th century. As an agent
in the Time Corps, you must stop him before he kills the grandparent
of someone important. And so on. This would use the &quot;Procedural Time&quot;
I'll describe below.
* Feng Shui. Played the roleplaying game with that name? Its metaplot
is that various faction are fighting over possession of &quot;Feng Shui
sites&quot;, places with great power which give their owners good luck in
life. It has time travel too. (Four discrete time periods - dystopic
future where an evil corporation owns all the sites, contemporary, and
two past eras. You can only travel to those specific years, and when a
year passes in &quot;contemporary time&quot;, it has also passed in the times to
which you can travel.)
* Where in Time is Carmen San Diego RL? Carmen San Diego hits! Carmen
San Diego bites! You hit Carmen San Diego with your cockatrice corpse.
Carmen San Diego is slowing down... maybe not.

Can you tell I'm more interested in time travel than parallel worlds?

Musing III: Cool mechanisms and puzzle opportunities. Can't go without
these.
* Procedurally generated future. Basically, everyone has a rudimentary
family tree backwards in time to the earliest point the game handles.
The PC and their nemeses really want to keep their family lines
secret. Could give lots of opportunities for game-breaking meanness.
* Terminator-style travel. Can't bring anything that's not alive
through. Makes the player both think twice about travelling
unnecessarily, and lets them come up with ideas to make stashes where
items will stay around for a few hundred years to be picked up in your
future. (Think graves.)

Well, I'm tired and incoherent. Give me some pointers to more
inspiration if you want. I might do this at some point. (Maybe a 7DRL.)
</POST>
