On 2007-09-14, Gerry Quinn &lt;ger ... @indigo.ie&gt; wrote:

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I played an infocom adventure once involving time travel.  It was one
&gt; of a series - I think it might have been Sorceror.
">

There are more of these nowadays: http://baf.wurb.com/if/genre/27

Many of those games probably don't deal with the paradoxes and causality
loops you can get from time travel and just treat time travel as means
of reaching interesting settings. _All Things Devours_, however,
implements a very intricate player-controllable time-travel system.
Definitely worth checking out.

Time travel games are most interesting when time travel actually takes
you in the past of the game itself. Instead of time travel from the 20th
century to ancient Egypt, travel back 10 minutes in game time. Now
instead of interacting with a completely different setting, you're
actually interacting with the history the player has been involved in.

The problem are causality loops. A classic Infocom puzzle has you
closing a causality loop for a rather perplexing object. But here the
implementors of the game have set up the loop for the player to stumble
into. What if the player in Nethack with a time travel patch collected
the Ascension Kit and the Amulet of Yendor and then time travelled to
turn 1 on dungeon level 1 and dropped the Kit in front of the version of
the PC who has just stepped in the dungeon?

Obviously, this is a bit of a problem. If the player could do this, then
the player should have had the kitted-out high-level PC pop in at the
beginning of the game and drop the kit. This of course didn't happen, as
the game had no idea what the player was going to do when the game
started.

One idea that I think has been discussed already is the one from the new
Prince of Persia games. Instead of transporting into the past as their
current physical self, the PC can rewind time, themself included, and
then act differently starting from some past point. This is basically
just a variation of the retry save game system made into a part of the
actual game. The future gets wiped out as time is rewound, so there can
be no Ascension Kit brought into the past. But since that's just
legitimized save scumming, it's not that novel or interesting.

Maybe there could be actual time travel, but with paradox checking. Once
the player has been in some situation at some point in time, that
situation must play exactly the same way after all subsequent time
travels, or paradox will ensue and the universe will be eaten. So
obviously the PC mustn't be seen or interact with their past self in any
way. The PC mustn't drop extra items or move existing items where the
past self has seen them. The PC mustn't alter the behavior of NPCs in
the past. Creatures and NPCs are quite difficult in this system, as it
really isn't easy for the player to figure out what consists or doesn't
consist of perturbing their behavior. My common sense says that any
interaction at all with an intelligent creature can cause unpredictable
and possibly very significant changes in its future behavior. Which
might be an argument for not having many other sentient creatures beyond
the player character in the setting where time travel takes place.

This is pretty much what All Things Devours does. It has the player
going back and forth in time in an empty building, with any interaction
with the PC from the past or the past state of the surroundings
resulting immediate game over. But I'm not sure if this is feasible
beyond a short and tightly crafted adventure game.

--
Risto Saarelma
