Actually there are several moments in Chronotrigger where you do meet
yourself and interfere with your own actions. One is simple, it's when
you replace Crono who is being killed by Lavos with his clone (and rescue
the original Crono in the process) -- it's all a movie sequence, so the
player cannot interfere in any way.

The more interesting moment is when you try to prevent Lucca's mother
becoming injured in one of their old experiments. You can see Lucca and
her family from upstairs, but you can't really reach them to interfere.

These are actually two places in the game where I really wanted to try
and interfere -- even when I knew it would be bad. You know, just to see
what happens. The limits imposed on me are really jarring in those two
moments.

